Product Task
\layout Standard

Ding Dong Doorentry Systems Ltd has commissioned our group to develop an
 idea for a new product.
 The product will be a door entry system that will allow a person within
 a building to use their own PC to view and communicate to the person at
 the door.
 Our task is to provide a prototype unit and the accompanying software for
 this project.
 The Market Potential for this device can be broken down down as:
\layout Subsection

Residential 
\layout Standard

Information from AmeriTech (a CCTV security firm) showed that you are five
 times less likely to be burgled if you have some form of surveillance scheme.
 The scheme we aim to provide would have to meet the competing needs of
 specific user groups.
 They can be broken down as:
\layout Subsubsection

Blocks of Flats 
\layout Standard

The increase of PC's in the home may allow this product to become an alternative
 to the standard door-entry system.
 According to a representative of Castle Security (a local security company)
 it would be unwanted by technophobes and those on a limited income for
 the forseeable future; the moment the majority of people are quite happy
 with the system they have; they can already identify anyone who comes to
 their door.
\layout Subsubsection

Accommodation with a servitor
\layout Standard

The servitors office would contain the PC and during the day people could
 be let in by sight only.
 During the night a form of security could be set on the main entrances.
 The potential here is for accommodation like halls of residence.
\layout Subsubsection

Semi /detached property
\layout Standard

Unlikely to be a market in smaller property, people will usually answer
 their door or look out to see who it is.
 There may be a market in countries like the USA where there is a significant
 gun culture, and residents already have a fear of intruders.
 The main market at present would be properties standing in a large area
 ie.
 estate houses.
 They can have entrances that are set a significant distance away from the
 property and could use the improved security of a visual communication.
 They are also likely to have the need and the money to invest in this form
 of security
\layout Subsection

Commercial
\layout Standard

This will be our proposed target market, in light of the Cullen Inquiry
 into the Dunblane report and the 1995 NHS Executive recommendation, the
