\layout Subsubsection

Education
\layout Standard

By encouraging schools to place this system at the entry points to their
 site; visitor movement could be controlled.
 During specific times the doors would be required to be left open, eg 8.15
 - 9.15, to allow pupil and teacher access but outside of these times access
 to the site will be controlled inside the school.
 Allowing the system to be configurable will allow this policy to be changed
 ie.
 the children could each have their own security device.
 Outside of school times the site will be closed to all but those with security
 access, which should have the added effect of cutting down vandalism.
 In situations were people are using part of the school out of hours then
 they will have to possess a security pass.
\layout Subsection

NHS 
\layout Standard

The system could be integrated to the front doors of wards that demand security
 for example maternity wards.
 Visitors will only be able to enter these areas if they have a specific
 reason to be there.
 The problems with existing NHS security include
\layout Itemize

security being lax because no-one monitors the video cameras.
\layout Itemize

security is bypassed by people who pretend to be some one else.
\layout Standard

The system we aim to supply must be quick and easy to use, since there may
 be emergency situations where the time is criticall, particularly a cardiac
 arrest alarm.
 Therefore the demands on the system will involve doctors needing instant
 access to wards; whilst still keeping a level of security that will satisfy
 parents.
